{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17633079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17633079"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:48:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:48:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17462"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17462"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0,0.03,0.91,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10152"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77292"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10152"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17462"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62799"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5488"},{"type":"tags","id":"11724"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23752"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23821"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77292"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher conducts a study examining the relationship between exercise and cardiovascular health. The study recruits participants by advertising at local gyms and fitness centres.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the main type of bias likely to affect this study?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Information bias","Recall bias","Observer bias","Selection bias","Measurement bias"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis study demonstrates \u003Cstrong\u003Eselection bias\u003C/strong\u003E because participants recruited from gyms and fitness centres are likely to be more health-conscious and physically active than the general population. This non-representative sampling limits the generalisability of findings to the broader population.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInformation bias\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when there are systematic errors in how data about exposures or outcomes are obtained from study participants.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecall bias\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when there are systematic variations in how participants remember prior events.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObserver bias\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when researchers\u0027 knowledge of the study hypothesis influences how they collect or interpret data.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasurement bias\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when there are systematic errors in measuring study variables or outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESelection bias is particularly problematic in epidemiological research as it can lead to conclusions that do not accurately reflect relationships in the target population. In this case, studying only gym attendees may overestimate the benefits of exercise in the general population.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Selection bias happens when participants do not represent the target population.","Common types of selection bias include volunteer bias, healthy worker effect, and loss to follow-up.","Selection bias can limit the generalisability of research findings to the broader population."],"references":["Ray, Sumantra, and others (eds), Oxford Handbook of Clinical and Healthcare Research, 1, Oxford Medical Handbooks (Oxford, 2016; online edn, Oxford Academic, 1 Mar. 2016), https://doi.org/10.1093/med/9780199608478.001.0001"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62799"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17462"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62799"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T15:33:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T15:33:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10152"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77292"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5326"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null